{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ffafacec-08b8-4c4b-a127-4cc4f4d3d689","content":"Yes, both approaches are correct for .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This iOS platform-specific tells MAUI to inset page content away from the notch/Dynamic Island and home indicator. You need the namespace:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This property on layout views (like `Grid`) lets a specific element extend *into* the safe area, even when the page has `UseSafeArea` enabled. Perfect for full-bleed background images:\n\n```xml\n<Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\n**Typical pattern:** Enable `UseSafeArea` on the page so text/buttons stay clear of the notch, then use `IgnoreSafeArea` only on the container holding your background image so it fills edge-to-edge. Your tutorial has the right idea.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"95448652-e9ed-433f-8856-56a7ada34241","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about these APIs in .NET MAUI, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved. Let me think about this:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` - This is a platform-specific property from Xamarin.Forms / early MAUI. \n\nThe `Page.UseSafeArea` attached property is available through the `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific` namespace and can be applied in XAML using the `ios:` prefix. Meanwhile, `IgnoreSafeArea` on layouts like Grid allows content to extend beyond the safe area boundaries even when the page respects safe area insets, which is useful for full-bleed background images. So `IgnoreSafeArea` on layout types lets them extend into the safe area—useful for background images that should go behind the notch. Both `UseSafeArea` and `IgnoreSafeArea` should work in .NET 10, and I'm thinking through how to show the XAML syntax with the proper iOS-specific namespace.","outputTokens":1112,"requestId":"7FD5:2F61F4:5E542C2:674E90D:69F15A57"},"id":"c367c56b-b0df-4a59-a5c3-243cf0913224","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:10:03.424Z","parentId":"a2dcb6af-47f3-4432-8f52-35142a0b6e92"}
